Resolves stenotype outlines to their expansions by walking a pre-compiled dictionary of constructs and types encoded as stroke sequences. The lookup pipeline converts a stroke sequence to a residual type, matches it against construct bases to find the most specific one, then fills its slots by consuming those residuals as nested types.

The core invariant: a lookup succeeds only if the entire stroke sequence is consumed and the walk reaches a terminal construct—partials are rejected even if they render text. `Walk` iterates all constructs once, scores matches by base length and fusion specificity (fused shape strokes score +1), and picks the highest. `WalkConstruct` then replays the residual type strokes against that construct's slots in the order specified by its `fillOrder` array, recursively expanding each slot via `ConsumeType`; any leftover strokes or incomplete obligations cause the lookup to fail.

The text arena is a simple bump allocator (8 KB fixed) that materializes rendered fragments as NUL-terminated strings; children finish before parents, so parent copies never overlap. Overflow truncates silently—the differential test against the Rust walker catches mismatches. Stroke limits are fixed: MAX_STROKES (64), MAX_SLOTS (64), MAX_ARITY (16) enforced at render time, never causing panics on user input.

Entry point: `Lookup(const StenoDictionaryLookup &) -> StenoDictionaryLookupResult` converts keystates to uint32_t, calls `Walk`, and returns invalid if text is null or terminal is false. The wire format—strokes as uint32_t keystates, constructs and types defined in `steno_generated_dictionary_data.h` (CONSTRUCTS array, TYPES array, CONSTRUCT_COUNT, TYPE_COUNT)—must stay in sync; mismatched data breaks all lookups silently.